                <h2>Conclusion First: Compliance Audits Are Not "Check When Problems Occur" but Fixed Actions That Must Be Performed Weekly</h2>
<p>Many overseas teams attribute account suspensions to platform tantrums or bad luck, but the truth is: more than 80% of suspension events have clear warning signals before they happen—it's just that no one systematically captures these signals.</p>
<p><strong>The essence of compliance auditing is not "satisfying platform reviews" but proactively managing account health.</strong> When you wait until ads are rejected or accounts are restricted to take remedial action, the loss has already occurred.</p>
<p>This article provides a directly actionable compliance audit SOP based on operational experience, applicable to Meta, TikTok, Google, and other mainstream overseas advertising platforms.</p>
<hr />
<h2>I. Pre-Launch Material Pre-Check: Blocking 70% of Potential Risks</h2>
<blockquote>
<p>"Spending 10 more minutes checking materials before launching ads is more cost-effective than spending 3 days appealing after suspension."</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Materials are the hotspot for compliance issues. Common problems include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Exaggerated claims</strong>: Using absolute terms like "first," "best," "absolutely"</li>
<li><strong>Click baiting</strong>: Overusing countdowns, limited purchase urgency, anxiety-inducing pop-ups</li>
<li><strong>Copyright issues</strong>: Using unauthorized logos, celebrity images, or popular IP elements</li>
<li><strong>Landing page inconsistency</strong>: Obvious differences between ad promises and page content</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Pre-check list (recommended for item-by-item verification before submission):</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Check Item</th>
<th>Specific Content</th>
<th>Common Issues</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Copy compliance</td>
<td>Contains absolute terms, medical efficacy claims</td>
<td>"100% effective," "cures"</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Image materials</td>
<td>Unauthorized logos/people/IP</td>
<td>Celebrity faces, competitor packaging</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Landing page match</td>
<td>Link destination consistent with ad content</td>
<td>Selling product A leads to page B</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Page loading speed</td>
<td>Mobile load time exceeding 3 seconds</td>
<td>High bounce rate judged as low quality</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>A utility app in the Southeast Asian market had its ad account suspended for 2 weeks because the landing page didn't display the locally required privacy notice. Missing just one line of text cost nearly $30,000 in advertising budget.</p>
<hr />
<h2>II. Account-Level Structural Audit: Don't Let "Chronic Disease" Drag Down Overall Weight</h2>
<p>The trigger for ad account suspension sometimes lies not in individual ads but in the account structure itself.</p>
<p><strong>Core audit items:</strong></p>
<h3>1. Payment Method Health</h3>
<p>Are there any abnormal transaction records on credit cards or payment accounts? Any chargebacks? <strong>Any payment abnormality triggers platform risk control mechanisms and can easily result in连带限制 (associated restrictions) on ad accounts.</strong></p>
<h3>2. Account Historical Behavior Consistency</h3>
<ul>
<li>Is the targeting region suddenly switched on a large scale? (For example, suddenly shifting from Europe and America to high-risk Southeast Asian markets)</li>
<li>Is the daily budget fluctuation too drastic? (Doubling daily budget easily triggers review)</li>
<li>Is the ad category crossover too large? (Suddenly shifting from e-commerce to financial category requires re-verification of qualifications)</li>
</ul>
<h3>3. Admin Permission Management</h3>
<p>Multi-person collaborative accounts are prone to "operation source confusion" problems. <strong>It is recommended to assign independent admin accounts to each operational role and regularly check the permission list to remove access from departed members.</strong></p>
<hr />
<h2>III. Periodic Account Health Review: 30 Minutes Per Week in Exchange for Account Security</h2>
<p>Many teams only check backend data when "something happens"—this is the biggest cognitive misconception.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended weekly fixed audit time, performing the following actions:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Check account notification center</strong>: Meta Business Manager, TikTok Ads Manager notification bars will proactively push potential risk warnings</li>
<li><strong>Review ad rejection reasons</strong>: If certain materials are rejected, investigate whether other similar issues exist</li>
<li><strong>Reconcile spend and conversion curves</strong>: If spend drops sharply but budget remains unchanged, ads are likely under review</li>
<li><strong>Backup account settings</strong>: Regularly export key information such as campaign structures and pixel event configurations</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Operational experience:</strong> A cross-border e-commerce team accidentally deleted core data from their ad account due to a team member's misoperation. Because they had made advance backups, they restored all campaigns in just 2 hours. Without the backup, reconstruction would have taken at least 1-2 days, and historical data would be irretrievable.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Implementation Recommendations: Make Auditing a Habit, Not a Task</h2>
<p>Whether the compliance audit SOP can truly be implemented depends on two key points:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Visualization</strong>: Use spreadsheets or kanban boards to record each audit result, forming a traceable issue checklist</li>
<li><strong>Clear accountability</strong>: Designate who is responsible for checking and who is responsible for remediation, avoiding the "everyone's in charge = nobody's in charge" dilemma</li>
</ul>
<p>For overseas teams managing multiple accounts, it is recommended to use aggregation tools to achieve unified cross-account health monitoring, reducing the cost of manual one-by-one checking.</p>
<p><strong>Compliance is not a cost but an investment in proactive risk management.</strong> Transforming auditing from a "firefighting action" into a "daily habit" will improve both account stability and advertising efficiency.</p>
